Anglo-Latin <i>cofferarius</i>. Compare   Coffer  . The modern English word <i>coffin</i> is a specialized development of this term, not attested until the 16th century.","History: Tristram Coffin came from Brixham, Devon, to Haverhill, MA, before 1647. An important line of his descendants is associated with Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffer","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>cofre</i>, <i>coffre</i>, <i>coffer</i> ‘box, chest’ (from Old French <i>cof(f)rehere</i>), used to denote a box or coffer maker (Old French <i>coffrier</i>), perhaps also for a treasurer.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Kaufer   or <b>Kauffer</b>."]},{"name":"Coffing","meanings":["English: variant of   Coffin  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":21,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":94,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Mrs. David Coffin was born in 1361, in England, her father, Coffin, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Coffin, was 26. She married David Coffin in 1391, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in her hometown, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1361–":"1361–Surnud","1361–Female":"1361–Surnud","1361–1400":"1361–1400","1392–1427":"1392–1427","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","England":"England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Alwington, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1361–":"1361–Kuollut","1361–Female":"1361–Kuollut","1361–1400":"1361–1400","1392–1427":"1392–1427","1334–Male":"1334–Kuollut","1336–Female":"1336–Kuollut","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","England":"England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Alwington, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":